What I will do in the next few minutes is to share some thoughts, to tell y=
ou about how we think about search and how we will take Bing forward. And t=
he purpose is to set the contest for today=E2=80=99s announcement. We take =
fundamentally a broad holistic view about search. To us search at its very =
core, it=E2=80=99s about understanding user intent and to bring information=
 and knowledge to help fulfill the intent. And the intent here is defined b=
roadly to meet the purpose of a user.

And it was that, as the fundamental end goal and the viewpoint, if you look=
 at all the surface area for search, today=E2=80=99s phone is a Qwerty box,=
 you type in keyboards, you get a list of results to pick from. It doesn=E2=
=80=99t have to be that way. In the future as the Web evolves the different=
 forms of capturing user intent, surface information, surface knowledge can=
 all change and evolve. By and large, in today=E2=80=99s form of a search i=
t serves as a gateway for users to access information, to discover what=E2=
=80=99s available in the Web and to interact with all the digital experienc=
e that=E2=80=99s in the consumer Web.

For Bing our aspiration is to go substantially beyond that. Our quest is to=
 build the capabilities and experience in Bing to fundamentally enable our =
users to make more informed decisions faster to better accomplish their pur=
poses. So, that=E2=80=99s fundamentally how we think about the product stra=
tegies going forward for Bing. And it is granted on how we think about the =
Web has evolved so far and how the Web is going forward, heading towards.

This blog post, I should clarify, wasn=E2=80=99t from this week: it was fro=
m 2010, when Bing was going to partner with Facebook to take down Google.

That didn=E2=80=99t happen, of course. Nor did vertical search, i.e. the id=
ea that specialized apps like Yelp or Trip Advisor would peel away search f=
rom Google. Instead Google changed search to provide different results base=
d on the type of search that was conducted: local searches featured Maps, t=
ravel searches featured booking options, etc. What was a constant were thre=
e things:

* Google was the default search for both browsers and, increasingly, mobile=
 phones.
* Google was the preferred and habituated search for nearly all users.
* Google had the best search results.

Some of the vertical search companies would object to this last point, at l=
east in their specific domain, but from a user perspective, search is searc=
h; no user wants to have to make a conscious decision about which search en=
gine to use based on what vertical their query falls into. They simply want=
 to search, which meant that Google only had to be good enough in the domai=
ns it was weaker in, because it was, on balance, good at everything. Bing +=
