=80=99m convinced that Bing + OpenAI is either.

Monetizable Panic
-----------------

I clipped some excerpts from Microsoft=E2=80=99s presentation yesterday, bu=
t today I wanted to focus on this bit from Yusuf Mehdi, Corporate Vice Pres=
ident of Search:

( https://videopress.com/embed/e6k2IfG9?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0 )

Let=E2=80=99s talk about the opportunity in search, and why we think we=E2=
=80=99re at the start of the next generation. With over 10 billion queries =
a day, we all know the search engine is an incredible tool. And yet, as the=
 web has grown, we have run into challenges. People are overwhelmed increas=
ingly with too many links when they are trying to find simple answers. In f=
act, 40% of the time when people click on search links they click back imme=
diately. That=E2=80=99s a sign they=E2=80=99re not finding what they want. =
And most notably, we have to adapt to search, versus the other way around. =
It turns out search works better if you give it fewer key words. You might =
be surprised to know that 75% of all searches are three keywords or less.

But we shouldn=E2=80=99t be surprised: search has remained fundamentally th=
e same since the last major inflection, when we moved from a directory appr=
oach to search, to an algorithmically approach to search. The user experien=
ce, and the underlying approach, are essentially the same as 20 years ago. =
A few keywords, and you get millions of links. But as the world around us h=
as changed, the way people use search has changed. We all know this. People=
 are trying to use search to do more than it was designed to do.

To illustrate that, let=E2=80=99s look at a breakdown of search queries by =
type to understand this point. Search queries today you can bucket them int=
o three serving three types of categories. The first is navigational. This =
is people searching for a website. When you need to renew your driver=E2=80=
=99s license, you need to go to the DMV. When you want to tell you friend a=
bout that great pizza place, you send them the web link. That=E2=80=99s wha=
t search was designed to do, and it does it super well. The second third of=
 categories are what we call informational. This is like =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=
=80=99s the weather forecast.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat was last night=E2=80=
=99s sports scores?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s today=E2=80=99s stock =
price?=E2=80=9D Search works great for that. But for anything more complex,=
 like =E2=80=9CI have to pick up this loveseat at the store, is it going to=
 fit in the back of my car?=E2=80=9D search is going to fall flat on that. =
The final third I would bucket in what we call =E2=80=9CEverything Else.=E2=
=80=9D These are typically more deep research in nature. This is things lik=
e trip planning, or complex shopping. An example query here that people are=
 putting in here is, =E2=80=9CCan you recommend a five-day itinerary to Mex=
ico City.=E2=80=9D For these search falls far short of the desired goal.

What this means, if you do the simple math, is that roughly half of all sea=
rches aren=E2=80=99t delivering the job that people want. If you go on that=
 10 billion queries, every second 50,000 people=E2=80=99s searches potentia=
lly go unanswered. This is why we believe it=E2=80=99s time for a new appro=
ach in search.

This is, obviously, the context for the introduction of Bing=E2=80=99s new =
OpenAI-powered chat interface, and I=E2=80=99m fine to grant Mehdi and Micr=
osoft the argument. Moreover, as an extremely heavy user of search, I certa=
inly feel that the quality of results has degraded over time, which, when y=
ou consider the fact that producing spammy SEO-optimized content has zero m=
arginal cost in terms of publishing and distribution =E2=80=94 and, soon en=
ough, zero marginal cost in terms of production, as AI is brought to bear =
=E2=80=94 is kind of inevitable.

Here=E2=80=99s the more pertinent question from a business model perspectiv=
e, though: what is the monetization potential of the three categories Mehdi=
 identifies? Google itself freely admits that most searches don=E2=80=99t m=
onetize at all; it still strives to do a good job on all of them because it=
 wants to be the choice for the search results that do.

This, though, highlights the challenges that Bing might face in displacing =
Google. The first is the distribution challenges. Google is the default sea=
rch in nearly every browser and on every phone. Microsoft could certainly b=
id Google out of that position =E2=80=94 Apple is a potential beneficiary o=
f Microsoft=E2=80=99s renewed commitment to search, as default iPhone searc=
h is the most accessible prize in terms of distribution =E2=80=94 but that =
would be a massive financial commitment without the commensurate advertiser=
 base and, frankly, search quality, that Google has. That=E2=80=99s the sec=
ond point: Bing is still Bing. It=E2=80=99s search just isn=E2=80=99t as go=
od, as websites still optimize for Google =E2=80=94 which crawls more sites=
 =E2=80=94 and it is Google that has the data advantage. The third issue, t=
hough, is what I wrote about last month ( https://stratechery.com/2023/more=
-on-google-and-ai-openai-integration-and-microsoft/?access_token=3DeyJhbGci=
OiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ=
9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0d=
HBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjMvbW9yZS1vbi1nb29nbGUtYW5kLWFpLW9wZW5haS1p=
bnRlZ3JhdGlvbi1hbmQtbWljcm9zb2Z0LyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNjc4NTM2NDQ5LCJpYXQiOjE2NzU=
5NDQ0NDksImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIi=
wic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVhZ=
CIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.lsIRODJ6J=
