Go back to the last time Google was thought to be in trouble, when the rise=
 of apps led to widespread predictions that vertical search apps would peel=
 away Google=E2=80=99s market share; Google significantly overhauled Search=
 to deliver vertical specific results for things like local, travel, etc., =
and introduced answers for common questions. Google also got a lot faster =
=E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s notable that =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m feeling lucky=E2=
=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t actually exist in practice because Google delivers s=
earch results now as you type. The end result was a company that continued =
to grow, even from its massive base=E2=80=A6

I suspect that Google will try to take a similar tack now: it helps that th=
e current iteration of chat interfaces are mostly useful for questions and =
topics that aren=E2=80=99t particularly monetizable anyways. Google could v=
ery well introduce chat-like responses, with the option to go deeper, for t=
he topics that make sense, while still delivering search results for everyt=
hing else, including the questions that actually monetize.

In short, while Google has looked like a mess this week, in some respects t=
hose signs of a panic are a positive indicator. Google does need to respond=
, and it is good news that the company seems aware of that reality. Moreove=
r, it still seems to me that Google can respond in a way that preserves its=
 most profitable verticals, precisely because those verticals are still wel=
l served by regular search.

Paradigms and Hardware
----------------------

One more bit about Google=E2=80=99s distribution advantage: one of the reas=
ons why Google=E2=80=99s position is more secure than it might seem is beca=
use of Android. Android runs on the majority of the world=E2=80=99s phones,=
 and Google search is the default. This is, of course, by design. Go back t=
o Bill Gurley=E2=80=99s seminal article The Freight Train That Is Android (=
 https://abovethecrowd.com/2011/03/24/freight-train-that-is-android/ ) :

Android, as well as Chrome and Chrome OS for that matter, are not =E2=80=9C=
products=E2=80=9D in the classic business sense. They have no plan to becom=
e their own =E2=80=9Ceconomic castles.=E2=80=9D Rather they are very expens=
ive and very aggressive =E2=80=9Cmoats,=E2=80=9D funded by the height and m=
agnitude of Google=E2=80=99s castle. Google=E2=80=99s aim is defensive not =
offensive. They are not trying to make a profit on Android or Chrome. They =
want to take any layer that lives between themselves and the consumer and m=
ake it free (or even less than free). Because these layers are basically so=
ftware products with no variable costs, this is a very viable defensive str=
ategy. In essence, they are not just building a moat; Google is also scorch=
ing the earth for 250 miles around the outside of the castle to ensure no o=
ne can approach it. And best I can tell, they are doing a damn good job of =
it.

The castle in Gurley=E2=80=99s analogy is Search, which leads to two observ=
ations: first, the fact that I just talked about Android as a reason to be =
optimistic about Search is to basically say that the strategy worked. Andro=
id is a moat! Second, one way to think about Microsoft=E2=80=99s approach t=
o Bing is that they see it as their Android relative to Google Search=E2=80=
=99s Windows: they don=E2=80=99t care if their only accomplishment is destr=
oying the value of the incumbent, because their core business is orthogonal=
. That is true as far as it goes: a resurgent Bing potentially leads to Mic=
rosoft subscription services, or highlights Azure AI capabilities to prospe=
ctive enterprise clients.

The difference, though, is that Android was riding a form factor shift: mob=
ile versus PC. New Bing, on the other hand, is only available on a desktop =
browser (the ideal setup for now, I would note, is Edge with Bing in the si=
debar, and Google as default search). What made mobile such an inflection p=
oint is that it reset everything: in the case of Intel, x86 was no longer l=
ock-in; in the case of operating systems, Windows was no longer an inevitab=
le choice. There is no corresponding hardware shift when it comes to AI, at=
 least not yet.

This gets at perhaps the biggest issue with these chat interfaces: they=E2=
=80=99re honestly kind of annoying to use. Typing full sentences is a pain,=
 and waiting for a response to be typed out is inefficient. What seems to m=
ake much more sense is voice, but that doesn=E2=80=99t work everywhere; som=
etimes it=E2=80=99s preferable to just type a couple of keywords and go fro=
m there.

None of this is meant to degrade Microsoft=E2=80=99s efforts. I think it=E2=
=80=99s absolutely fantastic the company is going after Google (which, I mi=
ght note, is a reminder that so-called =E2=80=9Cmonopolies=E2=80=9D based o=
n user preferences are always vulnerable). I should also add that Google fa=
ces real cost concerns: the company=E2=80=99s cost of revenue has increased=
 steadily over the last several years as it has incorporated AI into search=
, and conversation AI is very expensive. It=E2=80=99s reasonable to questio=
n the company=E2=80=99s long-term margin profile. I=E2=80=99m skeptical, th=
ough, that Google will take this lying down: the company has responded to t=
hreats before, and the messiness of this week does, counterintuitively, sug=
gest they are ready to do so once again.

